      answer:
        'Every modern CPU has at least two privilege levels: **kernel mode** (ring 0 on x86, EL1 on ARM) where privileged instructions and all memory are accessible, and **user mode** (ring 3 / EL0) where they\'re not. The kernel runs in the privileged mode; your code runs in the unprivileged one.\n\nThe enforcement is **hardware**, not software. The CPU\'s CPL bit (in the CS register segment selector on x86) decides what\'s allowed. Try a privileged instruction from user mode — `cli`, `hlt`, writing CR3 — and the CPU raises a general-protection fault, which the kernel turns into `SIGSEGV`.\n\nThe only ways to drop from user to kernel are gates the kernel set up: the **syscall** instruction, an **interrupt**, or an **exception**. All three atomically raise privilege and jump to a kernel-controlled entry point. User code can\'t pick the destination, only fire the gate. That\'s why "kernel mode" is a real boundary — it\'s enforced by transistors, not polite convention.',
