      question: 'What does `fork()` actually do, and why isn\'t it expensive for a 10GB process?',
      answer:
        '`fork()` creates a new process that\'s a near-duplicate of the caller. The kernel allocates a new PCB, copies most of the parent\'s fields, gives it a new PID, and returns. The child sees the same memory contents, same open FDs, same working directory.\n\nThe reason it\'s cheap even for huge processes is **copy-on-write (COW)**: the kernel doesn\'t physically copy the memory. It duplicates the page tables and marks all writable pages read-only in *both* parent and child. Each page is only physically copied when somebody tries to write it (a page fault triggers the COW handler).\n\nSo a 10GB process forks in microseconds. The cost shows up later: every page that either side writes triggers a fault and a copy. If the child immediately `exec`s (the common case for shell pipelines), almost nothing gets copied — `exec` unmaps everything and starts fresh.\n\nThe gotcha: long-lived forked processes (Redis BGSAVE, Postgres backends) can accumulate substantial COW copies over time and briefly double memory use. The "Redis fork OOM" pattern is exactly this.',
