      answer:
        'The scheduler picks which runnable thread runs next on each CPU. There are usually many more runnable threads than cores, so the scheduler **time-shares** the CPUs: each thread gets a slice, then the scheduler picks another, and so on. On Linux the default scheduler is **CFS** (since 2007), being replaced by EEVDF on newer kernels.\n\nA **context switch** is the act of changing which thread runs on a CPU:\n\n1. Save the current thread\'s CPU state (registers, RIP, RFLAGS) to its kernel stack.\n2. Update its scheduling info (time slice, vruntime).\n3. Pick the next thread from the runqueue.\n4. Switch address spaces if it\'s in a different process (write its page table root to CR3).\n5. Restore the new thread\'s saved state.\n6. Return to user mode in the new thread.\n\nDirect cost: ~1–3µs on x86-64. Indirect cost (cache and TLB pollution after switching) can be 10–100µs. Switches happen for three reasons: voluntary (thread blocked on I/O), involuntary (timeslice expired), or wake-up (a higher-priority thread became runnable). `vmstat 1` shows context switches/sec; `pidstat -w` breaks them out per process.',
