      answer:
        'When the CPU tries to translate a virtual address and the page table entry is **not present**, or has wrong permissions, the CPU raises a **page fault** (exception #PF). The fault handler reads CR2 (which holds the faulting address), finds the VMA that should cover it, and decides what to do:\n\n- **Demand-paged, never touched** → allocate a zero page, install the PTE, retry. (Minor fault, no I/O.)\n- **Swapped out** → read from swap, install PTE. (Major fault — slow.)\n- **Copy-on-write after fork** → copy the page, mark writable, install PTE. (Minor fault.)\n- **Stack growth** → extend the stack VMA, allocate, install. (Minor.)\n- **No VMA covers the address, or permission mismatch** → send `SIGSEGV`. (Crash.)\n- **Kernel bug accessing user-space wrong** → OOPS / panic.\n\nMost page faults are *normal* operating behavior, not bugs. `ps -o min_flt,maj_flt` shows the breakdown per process. Minor faults are microseconds; major faults are milliseconds (disk I/O). A high `pgmajfault` rate is a big red flag — the working set doesn\'t fit in RAM and the system is swapping or refaulting from file cache. That\'s **thrashing**, and the only real fixes are more RAM or smaller working set.',
