      answer:
        'The **TLB (Translation Lookaside Buffer)** is the CPU\'s cache of recent virtual-to-physical address translations. Without it, every memory access would require walking the 4-level page tables (4+ memory loads per access). Typical sizes: L1 dTLB ~64 entries, L2 ~1500 entries. A TLB hit costs ~1 cycle; a miss is 10–100 cycles for the page walk.\n\nThe TLB is **per-CPU**. When the kernel changes a page mapping — `munmap`, `mprotect`, `madvise(DONTNEED)`, freeing a page in an allocator — it has to invalidate the now-stale TLB entry on every CPU that might have cached it. That\'s a **TLB shootdown**: CPU 0 sends an inter-processor interrupt (IPI) to every other CPU, each runs an invalidation handler, acks. CPU 0 waits for all acks before continuing.\n\nCost: tens of µs per shootdown, scaling with core count. It\'s why "freeing memory" gets expensive on big machines, and why memory-intensive workloads benefit so much from **huge pages** (2MB or 1GB instead of 4KB) — fewer entries to manage, fewer shootdowns, larger TLB coverage. **PCID** on x86 (and ASID on ARM) tags TLB entries with a process ID so CR3 switches don\'t require a full flush.',
