      question: 'Why is mutex acquire usually free when the lock isn\'t contended? What\'s a futex?',
      answer:
        'A modern user-space mutex is **a single 32-bit integer in user memory**. The fast path uses a CAS (compare-and-swap) on that integer entirely in user space — no syscall, no kernel involvement. ~10–20 cycles when uncontended.\n\nWhen the lock IS contended, the kernel gets involved via the **futex (fast userspace mutex)** syscall. The protocol:\n\n```\nlock:\n  if CAS(state, 0, 1): return        // uncontended: no syscall\n  state = 2                           // mark "contended"\n  futex(state, WAIT, 2)              // park in kernel if still == 2\n\nunlock:\n  if atomic_store(state, 0) was 2:\n      futex(state, WAKE, 1)          // wake one waiter\n  else:\n      return                          // no contention: no syscall\n```\n\n`futex_wait(addr, value)` atomically says "go to sleep if `*addr == value`." The compare-and-sleep is atomic, so there\'s no race between "I saw it contended" and "I\'m now sleeping."\n\nThis is what `pthread_mutex_t`, `std::mutex`, Java\'s `synchronized`, Go\'s `sync.Mutex`, and futex-based POSIX semaphores all use. The user-space fast path is why mutex acquire feels free in the common case; the kernel only gets involved when threads actually fight for the lock.',
