      answer:
        'Modern CPUs are out-of-order and have store buffers, so the actual order in which one core\'s memory writes become visible to another core differs from the program order. The **memory model** says which reorderings are allowed.\n\n- **x86 (TSO — Total Store Order)**: stores are ordered with each other; the only weakening is that loads can be reordered *before* earlier stores to different addresses (store-load reordering, the store buffer is the cause).\n- **ARM, POWER (weakly ordered)**: all four pairwise reorderings (store→store, store→load, load→load, load→store) are legal unless you ask for a barrier.\n\nThe canonical break:\n\n```\nThread 1            Thread 2\nx = 1               r1 = y\ny = 1               r2 = x\n```\n\nOn x86, if Thread 2 sees `y == 1`, it also sees `x == 1`. On ARM, Thread 2 can legitimately observe `r1 = 1, r2 = 0` — Thread 1\'s stores became visible out of order.\n\nThe fix is **release/acquire pairs**: Thread 1 stores y with `memory_order_release`; Thread 2 loads y with `memory_order_acquire`. If T2 sees the released value, the spec guarantees it also sees everything T1 wrote before the release.\n\nCode that\'s correct on x86 by accident — relying on TSO — silently breaks on ARM. The fix is: use the high-level primitives (mutex, channel) that have correct happens-before edges baked in; if you reach for atomics, use explicit memory orderings; run ThreadSanitizer; test on ARM CI. "Works on my Mac" is no longer the safe assertion it was — Apple Silicon is ARM.',
